and check your answer.  (See .)

If it exists, find the inverse of the $2\times 2$ matrix

A=\begin{bmatrix}
6&3\\4&2
\end{bmatrix}

and check your answer.  (See .)

Let
D=\begin{bmatrix} 1 & -1 & 3 & -2 & 1\\ -2 & 3 & -5 & 3 & 0\\ 1 & -1 & 4 & -2 & 2\\ -1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & 4\\ 1 & 0 & 5 & -2 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
Compute the inverse of $D$, $\inverse{D}$, by forming the $5\times 10$ matrix $\augmented{D}{I_5}$ and row-reducing (). Then use a calculator to compute $\inverse{D}$ directly.

Let
E=\begin{bmatrix} 1 & -1 & 3 & -2 & 1\\ -2 & 3 & -5 & 3 & -1\\ 1 & -1 & 4 & -2 & 2\\ -1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & 2\\ 1 & 0 & 5 & -2 & 4 \end{bmatrix}
Compute the inverse of $E$, $\inverse{E}$, by forming the $5\times 10$ matrix $\augmented{E}{I_5}$ and row-reducing (). Then use a calculator to compute $\inverse{E}$ directly.

Let
C= \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 3 & 1\\ -2 & -1 & -4 & -1\\ 1 & 4 & 10 & 2\\ -2 & 0 & -4 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
Compute the inverse of $C$, $\inverse{C}$, by forming the $4\times 8$ matrix $\augmented{C}{I_4}$ and row-reducing (). Then use a calculator to compute $\inverse{C}$ directly.

exercise.solution:
Employ ,
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 3 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 & 0\\ -2 & -1 & -4 & -1 & 0 & 1 & 0 & 0\\ 1 & 4 & 10 & 2 & 0 & 0 & 1 & 0\\ -2 & 0 & -4 & 5 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \rref \begin{bmatrix} \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0 & 38 & 18 & -5 & -2\\ 0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 96 & 47 & -12 & -5\\ 0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0 & -39 & -19 & 5 & 2\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1} & -16 & -8 & 2 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
And therefore we see that $C$ is nonsingular ($C$ row-reduces to the identity matrix, ) and by ,
\inverse{C}= \begin{bmatrix} 38 & 18 & -5 & -2\\ 96 & 47 & -12 & -5\\ -39 & -19 & 5 & 2\\ -16 & -8 & 2 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

View this system as $\linearsystem{C}{\vect{b}}$, where $C$ is the $4\times 4$ matrix from  and $\vect{b}=\colvector{-4\\4\\-20\\9}$.
Since $C$ was seen to be nonsingular in   says the  solution, which is unique by , is given by

\inverse{C}\vect{b}=
\begin{bmatrix}
38 & 18 & -5 & -2\\
96 & 47 & -12 & -5\\
-39 & -19 & 5 & 2\\
-16 & -8 & 2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\colvector{-4\\4\\-20\\9}
=
\colvector{2\\-1\\-2\\1}

Notice that this solution can be easily checked in the original system of equations.

The coefficient matrix of this system of equations is

A=
\begin{bmatrix}
 1 & 2 & -1 \\
 2 & 5 & -1 \\
 -1 & -4 & 0
\end{bmatrix}

and the vector of constants is $\vect{b}=\colvector{-3\\-4\\2}$.  So by  we can convert the system to the form $A\vect{x}=\vect{b}$.   Row-reducing this matrix yields the identity matrix so by  we know $A$ is nonsingular.  This allows us to apply  to find the unique solution as

\vect{x}
=
\inverse{A}\vect{b}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
 -4 & 4 & 3 \\
 1 & -1 & -1 \\
 -3 & 2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\colvector{-3\\-4\\2}
=
\colvector{2\\-1\\3}

Remember, you can check this solution easily by evaluating the matrix-vector product  $A\vect{x}$ ().

We can reformulate the linear system as a vector equality with a matrix-vector product via .  The system is then represented by $A\vect{x}=\vect{b}$ where

A&=
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & -1 & 2 \\
1 & 0 & -2\\
2 & -1 & -1
\end{bmatrix}
&
\vect{b}
&=\colvector{5\\-8\\-6}

According to , if $A$ is nonsingular then the (unique) solution will be given by $\inverse{A}\vect{b}$.  We attempt the computation of $\inverse{A}$ through , or with our favorite computational device and obtain,

\inverse{A}=
\begin{bmatrix}
 2 & 3 & -2 \\
 3 & 5 & -4 \\
 1 & 1 & -1
\end{bmatrix}

So by , we know $A$ is nonsingular, and so the unique solution is

\inverse{A}\vect{b}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
 2 & 3 & -2 \\
 3 & 5 & -4 \\
 1 & 1 & -1
\end{bmatrix}
\colvector{5\\-8\\-6}
=
\colvector{-2\\-1\\3}
